Spring: It is a dependency injection framework that complements the existing JavaEE 

Inversion of Control : the process of moving the control of cobject creation form the application code to an external framework 

Alongside dependency injection Spring makes it esay for developers to use the existing APIs and Frameworks
    Ex: Spring JDBC is like a wrap aroud of the actual jdbc provided by oracle -> helps developers write sql statements in one line
    Ex: Spring ORM, Spring MVC

Spring Container: it is a component that comes with the spring spring framework which is responsible for creating objects, 
        storing them and injecting them whever required
    It maintains the complete lifecycle of objects (from creation to destruction)
    The container needs 2 thingd -> Beans & xml config

Beans = POJO [Plain Old Java Object] 

ApplicationContext -> this inteface in spring represents a container                       
    3 implementations:
        1. ClasspathXMLApplicationContext
            Loads bean definitions from an XML configuration file located in the classpath.
            Useful when configuration files are bundled inside the application (e.g., inside src/main/resources).
                Classpath - is a parameter that tells the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) and the Java compiler 
                where to look for user-defined classes, packages, and resources needed to run or compile a program.
        2. FileSystemXMLApplicationContext
            Loads bean definitions from an XML configuration file located in the file system (outside the classpath).
            Useful when configuration files are external to the application, allowing changes without redeploying the app.
        3. AnnotationConfigApplicationContext
            Loads bean definitions from Java-based configuration classes annotated with @Configuration and @Bean.

2 types of Dependency Injection:
    . Constructor injection
        <bean id="mathCheatObjectValue" class="MathCheat"/>
        <bean id="student" class="Student">
            <constructor-arg name="id" value="101"/>
            <constructor-arg name="mathCheat" ref="mathCheatObjectValue"/>
        </bean>

    . Setter injection
        <bean id="employee" class="com.javatpoint.Employee">
            <property name="id" value="101"/>
            <property name="name" value="John"/>
            <property name="city" value="New York"/>
        </bean>

Constructor Ambuigity Problem:
    When giveing values in xml file they are given as string and then based on the datatype in the constructor
     the type is resolved using parseInt/ pareFloat, etc
    But when there is more than 1 constructor with same no of parameters but diff
     data types then the abmiguity problem comes and the 1st constructor in the order willl be invoked
     Ex: add(int a, int b) 
         add(double a, double b)
    But if there is add(String a, String b) then this one will be invoked because the type has matched
    To resolve this ambiguity we use the "type" attribute
        Ex: <constructor-arg name = "a" value = "10" type = "int" /> 


    "index"attribute is used inside the <constructor-arg> tag to explicitly specify the position of the constructor parameter. 
    This helps Spring determine which constructor argument maps to which parameter
    ex: <constructor-arg index="0" value="10"/>
        <constructor-arg index="1" value="project"/>


