    We use the <ref> element -> similar to value this can also be used as an attribute or element(tag)

    Reference types can also be injected using p schema

For all the above examples instead of writing <bean id="xyz"/> we can write <bean name="xyz, z"/>
    In name attribute we can give multile values.

Difference btw Annotation based and Java based Configuratuion:
    Annotation-Based Configuration:
        Uses annotations directly inside classes (@Component, @Service, @Repository, @Controller, @Autowired, @Value, etc.).
        Beans are discovered automatically through component scanning.
        Ex:
            @Component
            public class Student {
                @Autowired
                private Address address;
            }
            You don’t explicitly define beans in a configuration class; 
            instead, Spring scans packages and registers annotated classes as beans.

    Java-Based Configuration
        Uses @Configuration classes with @Bean methods to explicitly declare beans.
        You write factory methods that return bean instances.
        Ex:
            @Configuration
            public class AppConfig {
                @Bean
                public Student student() {
                    return new Student(address());
                }

                @Bean
                public Address address() {
                    return new Address("Chennai", "600001");
                }
            }
        No need for XML; beans are defined programmatically but still managed by Spring.

Life cycle methods of Spring beans:
    1. init() -> Invoked after the creation and injection of spring bean
    2. destroy()

Life cycle methods can be configured in 3 ways:
    1. xml confiuration
            In the class which you want as a bean define 2 methods (name them as per your wish) 

            <bean id="myBean" class="com.example.MyBean"
                init-method="init"
                destroy-method="cleanup"/>

            Even after adding this the destruction method might not be called. You have to include -> 
            AbstractApplicationContext instead of ApplicationContext and          context.registerShutdownHook();

    2. Spring Interfaces
            You have to implement InitializingBean(for init method) and DisposableBean(for destroy method) Interfaces
            Override - afterPropertiesSet() & destory() methods respectively
            Here also 'registerShutdownHook()' this hook is required
    3. Annotations
            @PostConstruct
            @PreDestroy
            Inorder to use the above annotations with JDK 9 and above we need to add javax.annotation-api dependency in pom.xml
            By default spring doesn't enable all annotations
            So, if you are using any xml based connfig file then you have to enable support for these annotations
            But, you're using @Configuration classes, Spring Boot or plain Java config(Ex: AppConfig [java based configuration]), you don't need extra XML.

Dependency check:
    @Required: it is used to mark a bean property as mandatory.
    Applied on setter methods of bean properties.
    Inorder to use this you have to enable support for @Required in (Java-based / xml based configuration). The key is that Spring needs the RequiredAnnotationBeanPostProcessor registered in the application context.
    Modern replacement for @Required is @Autowired

Inner Beans:
    Used when a bean is needed only by one specific parent bean and doesn't need to be shared elsewhere in the container.
    . (xml based )inner beans are beans defined inside the <property> or <constructor-arg> element of another bean.
    . They do not have an id or name because they cannot be referenced outside their parent bean.
    . Inner Beans are mainly used when the dependency is private to one bean.

    XML based:
    <bean id="student" class="com.example.Student">
        <property name="address">
            <!-- Inner bean -->
            <bean class="com.example.Address">
                <property name="city" value="Chennai"/>
                <property name="zipcode" value="600001"/>
            </bean>
        </property>
    </bean>

    Java based:
    @Configuration
    public class AppConfig {

        @Bean
        public Student student() {
            // Inner bean equivalent: Address created only here
            Address address = new Address("Chennai", "600001");
            Student student = new Student();
            student.setAddress(address);
            return student;
        }
    }

    Annotation based:
    @Component
    public class Student {
        private Address address;

        public Student() {
            // Inner bean equivalent: Address created only here
            this.address = new Address("Chennai", "600001");
        }
    }

Scope of beans:
    . singleton (Default)
    . prototype - creates new objects every time
        Only for Spring MVC web application
    . request - only A new bean instance is created for each HTTP request.
    . session - A new bean instance is created for each user session.
        Only for Spring MVC Portlets
    . globalsession - similar to session, but applies to a global HTTP session in a Portlet environment 

