@Autowired:
    this can be used at
    Field level: Field injection is simplest but discouraged because it breaks testability and immutability.
    Constructor level: recommended approach as it ensures mandatory dependencies (dependencies cannot be null), 
        supports immutability, and is best for unit testing.
    Setter level : used when the dependency is optional or can change after object creation.

@Qualifier
    Used to resolve ambiguity when multiple beans of the same type exist in the Spring container.
    Spring normally injects dependencies by type.
    If there are two or more beans of the same type, Spring doesn’t know which one to use → results in:
    NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException
    1. Field Injection
        @Autowired
        @Qualifier("upiPayment")
        private PaymentService paymentService;

    2. Constructor Injection (Recommended)
        private final PaymentService paymentService;
        @Autowired
        public MyController(@Qualifier("creditCardPayment") PaymentService paymentService) 
        {    
            this.paymentService = paymentService;
        }

    3. Setter Injection
        @Autowired
        public void setPaymentService(@Qualifier("upiPayment") PaymentService paymentService) 
        {
            this.paymentService = paymentService;
        }


Spring expression language (SpEL):

    #  - this symbol tells the container that it should evaluate the following expression
    {} - We write our expression within {} (ex: {4+7})
            Ex: @Value("#{4+7}")
                @Value("#{5>6?22:33}")
    $  - used by Spring to inject values from application.properties.
            Ex: ${prop}
            prop=apple,banana,mango
    '${prop}' - Wrap it in SpEL string literal
    
    . Because SpEL is not Java.
        SpEL uses:
        'string' → string
        "string" → not valid SpEL string
    
        Ex: @Value("#{'${prop}'.split(',')}")

    . Maps cannot be injected using ${} alone — only #{ } can evaluate them into a real Java Map.
        my.map.values={key1:'val1', key2:'val2'}
        This is not valid Java syntax.
        Spring reads it as a String:
        "{key1:'val1', key2:'val2'}"
        So ${my.map.values} → is literally a raw string.
        need # because the inner ${my.map.values} becomes a Map ONLY inside a SpEL expression.
    
    . For list, set and map you should use #
    . For arrays $ is suffucient

    . Property placeholder - in Spring it refers to the ${...} syntax 
            that allows you to inject values from an external properties file 
    
    Using static methods:
        T(class_name).method(parameters)
        Ex: @Value("#{T(java.lang.Math).abs(-99)}")
    
    Accessing Static variables:
        Similar to the above one
        Ex: @Value("#{T(java.lang.Integer).MIN_VALUE}")

    Creating Objects:
        Ex: @Value("#{new Integer(88)}")

    Expressing Boolean types:
        Ex: @Value("#{2+4 > 5}")
            private boolean isTrue;
        You write any expression that evaluates to True

